<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-323-792  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 323 792.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  April 9 1990 n265 p20(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM storage on track. (the company fulfills user requirements form automated storage management)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schindler, Paul E. Jr.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Guide Storage Management Group, a committee within an IBM userorganization that develops policies on computer storagemanagement, says IBM is on target in meeting the group'srequirements set forth in a 1983 report, 'Requirements for Futuresof Storage Management.' IBM responded to the requirements with itsData Facility System Managed Storage (DFSMS) product line.andP;  IBMshipped the first components in 1988 and plans to ship the finalcomponents in June 1990.andP;  Although potential customers fear thesystem might be too complex, current customers, who praise thesystem, dismiss the fears.andP;  One IBM spokesperson suggests customerdemands drove DFSMS's development.andP;  The system, she feels, offersusers tools that simplify storage management.andP;  DFSMS runs onMVS/XA and MVS/ESA operating systems.andP;  The company is researchingcompatibility with other operating systems and utilities that willenhance system performance.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     User NeedsUser GroupsStorage AllocationMemory ManagementCapacity ManagementMainframe Computers.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>